lexUnit.name: thud.v
lexUnit.definition: COD: move, fall, or strike something with a thud.

sentence.text: His legs thudded on and on , but the movement was mechanical , with no spirit in it .
A moth thudded into the parchment lampshade and blundered round , trying to escape .
An arrow thudded on his helmet .

Marching along the street , with boots thudding and fingers slapping ( a peculiarly skinhead mannerism ) , all wearing the same clothes and the same haircut , the skinheads presented an image of power .
I must have underestimated the benefit of my practice with the neighbour 's cat , since my attempt seemed to sail on and on before it thudded to the ground .
The bird had thudded against the wallpaper and started to flop downwards and then swooped round and up , seeming ignorant of the opening through which it had entered .
The sea roared like a pride of hungry lions , thudding against the side of the ship like a thousand battering-rams , so that it seemed that at any moment it must break through and drown them all .
Omar said the rocks continued to thud against her body for what seemed to be an interminable time .
And as the horse thudded over the frozen grass of the common land and came to the high road in a clatter of hooves , she sensed , beneath the fear , some ripple of excitement .
I heard Jean-Claude thud down the stairs and greet the man at the door .
Then , suddenly , he was running , his arms flailing wildly , his bare feet thudding against the dark earth .
By late afternoon , a full-scale battle had broken out with rockets and grenades exploding regularly and bullets thudding into the walls .
He heard a click and stepped back quickly as the bolt thudded into the wall of the derelict house behind him .
The door slammed back on its hinges and thudded into the wall .
It was cool on the terrace , and quiet enough to hear the waves thudding on to the Plage des Basques a long way below .
His back thudded against the wall and he scraped along it towards the door , still giddy with fear .
The plane swooped above them and thudded into the earth .
